    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense. i didnt know they needed to be that acidic. if i do end up needing to fix the ph, what's the best way to do that? should i be adding stuff directly to the ground or mixing it into the dirt first?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Fixing the pH of your soil, especially for blueberries, is a delicate process. You can try adding amendments directly to the soil, but you need to be careful not to overdo it, as too much of anything can upset the delicate balance.\n\nFor lowering the pH, you'll generally want to use something like elemental sulfur or aluminum sulfate. These are the standard tools for this job. Mix them thoroughly into the top few inches of the soil before you plant or apply them. It’s important to mix them in well, or you'll just have pockets of high pH and low pH, which is a real mess.",
      "source": "target",
